{{orphan|date=March 2012}}

'''DeconGel''' is a gel used to clean up after [[Chemical spill|chemical]] and [[nuclear disaster]]s.<ref>{{Citation |last=Zimmerman |first=Eilene |date=25 May 2011 |title=Blue goo sucks up toxic waste |work=CNNMoney |url=http://money.cnn.com/2011/05/25/technology/toxic_waste_cleanup_goo/index.htm |accessdate=23 June 2011}}</ref>  DeconGel was used after the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima nuclear disaster]] in Japan to remove high levels of radiation from the Asahimachi Baptist School, after the March 11, 2011 earthquake and subsequent tsunami compromised reactors and cooling baths at [[Tokyo Electric Power Company|TEPCO]]’s Daiichi Nuclear Power Station. The product has been tested by numerous agencies and organizations in Japan including first responders, nuclear power plant operators, and private companies.

