{{Infobox Convention | name = Southern Comfort Conference | image = | caption = | status = Active | genre = [[Transgender]] community | venue = | location = [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]] | country = United States | first = 1991 | last = 2016 | organizer = | filing = | attendance = | website = http://sccfla.org/ }} The '''Southern Comfort Conference''' is a major<ref>{{Cite book | last = Erhardt | first = Virginia | authorlink = | title = Head over heels: wives who stay with cross-dressers and transsexuals | publisher = Haworth Press | date = 2007 | location = | page = 11 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=8ycEAQAAIAAJ&q=%22southern+comfort+conference%22&dq=%22southern+comfort+conference%22&lr=&client=firefox-a | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-7890-3094-8}}</ref> [[transgender]] conference that has taken place annually since 1991.<ref>Eleanor J. Brader, [http://www.conducivemag.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=91:trans-health-care-reform-its-about-life-and-death829 "Trans Health Care Reform: It's About Life and Death."] ''Conducive'' August/September 2009.</ref> It features seminars, events, speeches by prominent people in the [[LGBT]] community,<ref name="jarvie"/> numerous vendors catering to transgender and [[transsexual]] people, and more, and is known as the largest,<ref name="jarvie">{{Cite news | last = Jarvie | first = Jenny | title = The Nation; Transitioning into new jobs, genders; At the first transgender career expo, men and women meet companies that accept them for who they are becoming | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | location = | page = A.18 | language = | publisher = | date = 2007-09-16 | url = https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/latimes/access/1336473091.html?dids=1336473091:1336473091&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+16%2C+2007&author=Jenny+Jarvie&pub=Los+Angeles+Times&desc=The+Nation%3B+Transitioning+into+new+jobs%2C+genders%3B+At+the+first+transgender+career+expo%2C+men+and+women+meet+companies+that+accept+them+for+who+they+are+becoming.&pqatl=google | accessdate = 2009-10-21}}</ref> most famous{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}}, and pre-eminent such conference in the United States.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Federation of Film Societies | first = | authorlink = | title = Film ... the magazine of the Federation of Film Societies | publisher = British Federation of Film Societies | date = 2001 | location = | page = 27 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=LX0HAQAAIAAJ&q=%22southern+comfort+conference%22&dq=%22southern+comfort+conference%22&lr=&client=firefox-a | doi = | id = | isbn = }}</ref> The organization offers scholarships to some attendees.<ref name="bagby">Dyana Bagby, [http://www.sovo.com/2009/10-2/news/localnews/10676.cfm "'It's like my world': Southern Comfort Conference provides safe space for trans people."] ''[[Southern Voice (newspaper)|Southern Voice]]'' 2 October 2009.</ref>
The conference provided the title for<ref>{{Cite news | last = Guthrie | first = Marisa | title = Television; Regular folks; `Southern Comfort' follows a transsexual couple battling cancer and prejudice | newspaper = [[Boston Herald]] | location = | page = S.32 | language = | publisher = | date = 2002-04-12 | url = | accessdate = 2009-10-21}}</ref> and is featured heavily in the 2001 documentary ''[[Southern Comfort (2001 film)|Southern Comfort]]'', about the life and death of [[Robert Eads]], whose goal in 1998 was to live long enough to attend the conference.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Bernard | first = Sheila Curran | authorlink = | title = Documentary storytelling: making stronger and more dramatic nonfiction films | publisher = Focal Press | date = 2007 | location = | page = 28 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=NjTvpSuIAnwC&pg=PT42 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-240-80875-8}}</ref> Eads succeeded, and his speech at the conference is featured in the documentary.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Zad | first = Martie | title = Memorable Film Clips of History | newspaper = [[The Washington Post]] | location = | pages = | language = | publisher = | date = 2002-04-14 | url = | accessdate = 2009-10-21}}</ref> In honor of the memory of Eads, the conference offers health exams through the annual "Robert Eads Health Project"<ref name="bagby"/><ref>[http://www.sccatl.org/TRANSHEALTH/SCCTRANSHEALTH.htm "Robert Eads Trans Health Project."] Southern Comfort Conference. Accessed 02 May 2010.</ref> in collaboration with the Trans Health Initiative at the [[Feminist Women's Health Center (Atlanta, GA)|Feminist Women's Health Center]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.feministcenter.org/health-wellness-services/trans-health-initiative/robert-eads-health-project-fair |title=Robert Eads Health Project Fair|publisher= Feminist Women's Health Center of Atlanta |accessdate=June 29, 2012}}</ref>
The conference has built a reputation as a safe place for LGBT people with a familial atmosphere,<ref name="bagby"/> and aims at inclusiveness.<ref>{{Cite book | last = Boyd | first = Helen | authorlink = | title = My husband Betty: love, sex, and life with a crossdresser | publisher = Thunder's Mouth Press | date = 2003 | location = | page = 278 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=vCT70HjI_a4C&pg=PA278 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-1-56025-515-4}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last = Watts | first = Trent | authorlink = | title = White masculinity in the recent South | publisher = LSU Press | date = 2008 | location = | page = 198 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=03_SyPiMaroC&pg=PA198 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-8071-3314-9}}</ref> It attracts people from all over the United States, offering the opportunity for social and other interaction.<ref>{{Cite book | last = O'Keefe | first = Tracie | authorlink = |author2=Katrina Fox | title = Trans people in love | publisher = Routledge | date = 2008 | location = | page = 121 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=AigQSatPMgAC&pg=PA121 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-7890-3572-1}}</ref> From the conference's founding in 1991 until 2014, the conference was held in Atlanta, Georgia. At the conclusion of the 2014 Southern Comfort Conference, the board of directors announced that SCC 2015-2017 will be held in Fort Lauderdale, Florida.
With support from the Greater Fort Lauderdale Convention and Visitor Bureau, the 2017 conference was to be held from September 14–17 at The Riverside Hotel in Fort Lauderdale<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sccfla.org/|title=Home|website=Southern Comfort Transgender Conference}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sunny.org/lgbt/transgender/|title=transgender|website=www.sunny.org}}</ref> However it was cancelled because of [[Hurricane Irma]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sccfla.org/news/2017/9/6/sctc-2017-cancelled-due-to-hurricane-irma |title=SCTC 2017 Cancelled due to hurricane Irma |date=2017-09-06 |access-date=2018-01-27}}</ref> The 2018 conference is to be held from September 6-8.
