{{about|the novel|the film adaptation|The Osterman Weekend (film)}} {{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Osterman Weekend | title_orig = | translator = | image = File:TheOstermanWeekend.jpg | caption = First edition | author = [[Robert Ludlum]] | illustrator = | cover_artist = | country = [[United States]] | language = [[English language|English]] | series = | subject = | genre = [[Thriller novel]] | publisher = [[World Publishing Company|World Publishing]] | pub_date = 1972 | english_pub_date = | media_type = Print ([[Hardback]] & [[Paperback]]) | pages = 315 pp | isbn = 0-529-04547-8 | dewey = 813/.5/4 | congress = PZ4.L9455 Os PS3562.U26 | oclc = 279044 | preceded_by = | followed_by = }}
'''''The Osterman Weekend''''' is a thriller novel by [[Robert Ludlum]]. First published in 1972, it was the author's second book. The novel was the basis for the [[The Osterman Weekend (film)|film of the same title]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Canby|first=Vincent|authorlink=Vincent Canby|title=Screen: 'The Osterman Weekend'|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=9A04E7D81739F937A35752C1A965948260&partner=Rotten%20Tomatoes|accessdate=21 April 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=4 November 1983}}</ref>
==Plot== John Tanner, Director of News of a US TV network, is convinced by a [[CIA]] agent that the friends he has invited to a weekend in the country are engaged in a conspiracy, called Omega, that threatens national security. But then everything John Tanner thinks he knows about his closest friends is overturned, and he is set against them. But when Omega finally reveals itself, he realizes that he has been manipulated from the very start.
